    "recipe_name": "Marinara Sauce",
    "ingredients": [
        "2 tablespoons olive oil",
        "1 large onion, chopped",
        "2-3 cloves garlic, minced",
        "1 (28 ounce) can crushed tomatoes",
        "1 (15 ounce) can tomato sauce",
        "1 (6 ounce) can tomato paste",
        "1/2 cup water (or red wine for richer flavor)",
        "1 teaspoon dried oregano",
        "1/2 teaspoon dried basil",
        "1/4 teaspoon red pepper flakes (optional, for a little heat)",
        "1 teaspoon sugar (to balance acidity)",
        "Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste",
        "Fresh basil leaves, for garnish (optional)"
    ],
    "recipe_instructions": "1. Heat olive oil in a large pot or Dutch oven over medium heat. Add the chopped onion and cook until softened, about 5-7 minutes.\n2. Add the minced garlic and cook for another minute until fragrant, being careful not to burn it.\n3. Stir in the crushed tomatoes, tomato sauce, tomato paste, and water (or red wine).\n4. Add the dried oregano, dried basil, red pepper flakes (if using), and sugar. Season with salt and pepper to taste.\n5. Bring the sauce to a simmer, then reduce the heat to low, cover, and let it cook for at least 30 minutes, or up to an hour, stirring occasionally. The longer it simmers, the more the flavors will meld.\n6. Taste and adjust seasonings as needed. If the sauce is too thick, add a little more water or broth. If it's too acidic, add a pinch more sugar.\n7. Serve hot over your favorite pasta, or use as a base for other dishes. Garnish with fresh basil if desired."
}
